  urldate = {2025-07-15},
  abstract = {Using multi-element abundances from the SDSS APOGEE survey, we investigate the origin of abundance variations in Milky Way (MW) disk stars on the "high-\${\textbackslash}alpha\$ plateau," with \$-0.8{\textbackslash}leq{\textbackslash}rm\{[Fe/H]\}{\textbackslash}leq-0.4\$ and \$0.25{\textbackslash}leq{\textbackslash}rm\{[Mg/Fe]\}{\textbackslash}leq0.35\$. The elevated [\${\textbackslash}alpha\$/Fe] ratios of these stars imply low enrichment contributions from Type Ia supernovae (SNIa), but it is unclear whether their abundance patterns reflect pure core-collapse supernova (CCSN) enrichment. We find that plateau stars with higher [Fe/Mg] ratios also have higher [X/Mg] ratios for other iron-peak elements, suggesting that the [Fe/Mg] variations in the plateau population do reflect variations in the SNIa/CCSN ratio. To quantify this finding, we fit the observed abundance patterns with a two-process model, calibrated on the full MW disk, which represents each star's abundances as the sum of a prompt CCSN process with amplitude \$A\_\{{\textbackslash}text\{cc\}\}\$ and a delayed SNIa process with amplitude \$A\_\{{\textbackslash}text\{Ia\}\}\$. This model is generally successful at explaining the observed trends of [X/Mg] with \$A\_\{{\textbackslash}text\{Ia\}\}/A\_\{{\textbackslash}text\{cc\}\}\$, which are steeper for elements with a large SNIa contribution (e.g., Cr, Ni, Mn) and flatter for elements with low SNIa contribution (e.g., O, Si, Ca). Our analysis does not determine the value of [Mg/Fe] corresponding to pure CCSN enrichment, but it should be at least as high as the upper edge of the plateau at \${\textbackslash}rm\{[Mg/Fe]\}{\textbackslash}approx0.35\$, and could be significantly higher. Compared to the two-process predictions, the observed trends of [X/Mg] with \$A\_\{{\textbackslash}text\{Ia\}\}/A\_\{{\textbackslash}text\{cc\}\}\$ are steeper for (C+N) but shallower for Ce, providing intriguing but contradictory clues about AGB enrichment in the early disk.},
